### Establishing Competitive Equilibrium

Price prediction and demand anticipation are determinants on whether a market is able to establish competitive equilibrium, a concept where demand and supply are fairly matched to price. 

This proved to be difficult for the traditional physical infrastructure industry, where transparency and data availability impacted prices for consumers in imbalanced economies. Profit maximization with diminishing revenue growth impose limits on resource utilization, as discussed for the telecom industry with oversaturated services and underserved niches.

DeWi protocols use the network token as a balance for supply and demand. Tokens are proportionally emitted to reward coverage, with factors such as data quality, resource usage, and network-determined necessity.

[Hivemapper](https://docs.hivemapper.com/), a dash-mounted camera sensor network, offers APIs for timely data from roadside imaging. Close to 500 million kilometers of roads have been mapped, with a 32% global coverage of 19 million kilometers in total of unique roads. 

Dynamic $HONEY rewards on mapping routes are accessible in-app for vehicle operators, calculated by the protocol based on the uniqueness and demand to map the path. Hivemapper prices demand with map credits, a USD-pegged utility token used by consumers to compensate the network and predict demand, controlling the $HONEY supply to fulfill demand with relative scarcity, as to maintain competitive equilibrium.

Utility tokens establish competitive equilibrium through decentralized autonomous protocols to disrupt markets in closed sectors to enter into equitable competition, consumer fairness, and new revenue-generating opportunities with cryptocurrency.
